JOHANNESBURG - Retailer Steinhoff has warned that the value of its write-downs might be $7.2-billion (R88.6-billion) more than initially reported in December. Auditor PwC says additional write-downs will need to be recorded. WATCH: Two cases of insider trading registered in Steinhoff scandal Overstated profits and off-balance-sheet entities that weren't handled properly will result in hefty additional asset write-downs. Steinhoff has confirmed it’s facing five lawsuits, including one by its former chairman Christo Wiese. The company has lost at least 96 percent of its value since financial irregularities were reported in December. The company's first-half financials will be tabled next month. eNCA